    <stitle>International&#174; T 444E Diesel Engine - Model Years Late 1997 to 2003 - Mounting Engine On Stand</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsection id="Section1" svcsectype="enginesec" division="engine" date="02/09/2002">
        <title>Mounting Engine On Stand</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="mount" graphiccount="4">
            <title>Mounting Engine On Stand</title>
            <figure id="f1200101" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg2/EG2620.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Location of Coolant Drain Plugs</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Right Coolant Drain Plug</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Oil Level Gauge</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Left Exhaust Manifold</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Left Coolant Drain Plug</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Oil Cooler/Filter Header</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drain the coolant from the crankcase by removing two coolant drain plugs. The drain
                    plugs are located at the rear of the crankcase, behind the exhaust manifolds on each side of the
                    engine.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After the coolant has drained, install coolant drain plugs into crankcase and tighten.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dispose of the coolant according to local regulations.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1200102" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3256.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Location of Oil Drain Plug</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Oil Pan</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Oil Drain Plug</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the oil drain plug. Allow the oil to drain into a suitable container.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After oil has drained, install the oil pan drain plug and tighten to the special torque
                    value.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dispose of the oil according to local regulations.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1200103" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3307.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Removing Oil Level Gauge</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Oil Level Gauge</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Stud Nut</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Right Exhaust Manifold</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen the stud nut that secures the slotted oil level gauge mounting bracket to the
                    right exhaust manifold. Remove the oil level gauge.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or possibly death, attach the hoist hook lifting bracket at the
                        engine lifting eyes before lifting the engine. Failure to do so can cause the engine to lift on
                        one end and swing out, injuring any personnel standing in the area.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Attach the hoist hook lifting bracket at the engine lifting eyes. Use a safety catch on
                    the hoist hook when lifting the engine.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or possibly death, or engine damage, use only grade 8 or greater
                        metric bolts when mounting the engine to the stand. Other bolts may sheer, causing the engine to
                        fall from the engine stand.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>For specific directions on the safe use of engine mounting stands and adapter plates, refer to
                        the manufacturer's instructions included with these parts.
                    </para>
                </note>
                <note>
                    <para>Use the correct engine stand adapter plate when mounting the engine to the stand.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f1200104" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg3/EG3174.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Installing Engine Stand Adapter Plate to Engine</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Engine Mounting Adapter Plate</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Spacer</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Mounting Bolts (3)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position and secure engine stand mounting adapter plate to right side of engine. Use
                    three grade 8 bolts.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mount engine to stand using the specified adapter plate and grade 8 or greater mounting
                    bolts.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
